THE Pension Funds Operators Association of Nigeria has said it plans to launch a pension women’s network to enable the females in the industry to interact with each other more, network and build a strong community for career advice and support as the need arises. This was disclosed during a webinar hosted by PenOp, where senior executives in the pension industry had engaging sessions. During the event, the female leaders spoke about challenges of being in a leadership positions as women and how professionalism, tenacity, great support and continuous learning got them to where they were. Most of the audience were females within the pension industry. The Chief Executive Officer, Access PFC, Idu Okwuosa, advised young women during the panel discussion on how to handle challenges confronting their career. “Take the highway, choose your fight and don’t let the distractions get to you and you’ll make it to the top,” she said. The General Manager, Progress Trust CPFA, Joy Ojakovo, said, “As a woman, you can’t do it alone, you need to build alliances, have a support structure to be able to grow and to lean on when need arises.” Copyright PUNCH. Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com